A violent earthquake registering 6.9 on the Richter scale rocked Northern California on Tuesday causing widespread damage throughout the San Francisco Bay area.
A section of both the San Francisco Bridge and the Oakland-San Francisco Bridge collapsed.
Buildings also collapsed and fans at the World Series game in Candlestick Park were terrified as the stands swayed.
A 1988 US Geological Survey predicted the area where the quake actually occurred contrary to studies predicting the next "big one" would be in the Los Angeles area.
President Bush directed $273 million in aid although coffers were strained from response to Hurricane Hugo.